Merge pull request #203 from jdkoren/plugin_options_2

Plugin options handling
Update uses of hasOption() to hasSquidbOption()
add getEnvOptionValue()

Make addPlugin() private

With the current plugin architecture, it doesn't make much sense for
outsiders to call this method. Clients can't really change the
PluginEnvironment, which means any code that runs will be part of a
plugin. Plugins are instantiated for each model spec, but addPlugin()
adds to the global list of plugins, so a plugin calling addPlugin()
would almost definitely be broken already.
Workaround for no String.join below Java 8
Report apt option keys specified by custom plugins

Merge pull request #111 from yahoo/constant_class_loading_order

Add the @Constants annotation for constant holding static inner classes in

Add the @Constants annotation for annotating static inner classes in model specs that hold constants

Most constants can safely be copied directly to the generated model. However, constants that are defined using table schema fields
(e.g. from Properties, Table, View, like public static final Order DEFAULT_ORDER = Model.COLUMN.asc()) may run into class loading
order issues where the fields needed to initialize the constant have not yet themselves been initialized at class loading time.
(This is discussed in more detail in issue 110, https://github.com/yahoo/squidb/pull/110).

This commit allows constants to be declared in a static inner class of the model spec, effectively deferring initialization
of copied constants until after the full schema has been initialized. The old behavior of directly copying constants has been
left intact so those who don't need this control over class loading order can use things as they always have.

Merge pull request #110 from lnikkila/fix-constant-initialisation-order

Initialise copied constants after everything else

Initialise copied constants after everything else

This makes it possible to reference e.g. properties defined in the generated
model from constants in the spec. Some useful use cases for such constants
include defining a natural order for the model or some commonly used queries so
that they can be accessed easily.

If these are defined before the `static final` class variables they're trying to
reference, it will lead to unexpected behaviour since those dependencies will be
`null`.

For instance, the following seems to work fine when defined in a spec and used
from a model, but only because `Query.select` defaults to selecting everything
when the parameter is `null`:

```
public static final QUERY_ALL = Query.select(Model.PROPERTIES).freeze();
```

The following, on the other hand, will crash with a `NullPointerException` since
`Model.ID` hasn't been initialised yet:

```
public static final DEFAULT_ORDER = Model.ID.asc();
```

Detailed information about the initialisation order of class variables can be
found in the [Java Language Specification][1].

[1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.3.2.1

Refactor how queries that need validation are handled

With the ability to use a Query anywhere a Field was valid by using Query.asFunction, it became too difficult to manage when a root query would need to be validation for suspicious WHERE clauses. This new approach refactors SQL statement compilation to set an AtomicBoolean flag if any part of the Query being compiled requires validation. Before execution, SquidDatabase will check this flag. If it is set, it will compile again with the extra parentheses like it always has.

This refactor has the added benefit of cleaning up some of our SQL generation by bundling necessary builder objects (the SQL StringBuilder, the List<Objects> bound arguments, and the AtomicBoolean flag) into a single SqlBuilder class that can be passed to all SQL generating methods.

Hack for handling null characters in inlined string literals

Java treats strings differently than C does. In Java, null characters are allowed. In C, they end the string. So if we inline a Java string that contains null characters as a literal, the parsing will just fail. Of course, the best option is to bind all such strings as arguments rather than inlining them, but when there are too many arguments, we fall back to inlining, so we need a fallback. This commit enhances string literal sanitization to replace occurrences of null characters with SQL string concatenations of CAST(x'00' AS TEXT), which converts a literal blob of the null character to a string.

Throw if attacher in transaction on current thread

Android will throw an exception if you try to attach a database while
the attacher has an open transaction on the current thread. This was
suppressed by tryExecSql and we returned null instead.

The fix to acquire the exclusive lock on API 16+ if WAL is enabled
now causes an exception to be thrown in this situation; if WAL is not
enabled, or on API 15 and below, null was still returned. This change
makes the behavior consistent in all cases.

Acquire exclusive lock before attach if WAL enabled
